You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice periodically hangs and experiences thread starvation. Thread dumps reveal multiple threads are blocked in the `BLOCKED` state at `java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap.computeIfAbsent`. Below is the simplified snippet of the custom cache loader used within a Spring-managed singleton bean:

java
@Service
public class CustomCacheService {
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, String> localCache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public String getOrCompute(String key) {
        return localCache.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> {
            if (k.endsWith('-fallback')) {
                return 'STATIC_DEFAULT';
            }
            return localCache.computeIfAbsent(k + '-fallback', fk -> resolveFromExternalSystem(fk));
        });
    }

    private String resolveFromExternalSystem(String key) {
        return 'external-value';
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a Spring-based application running on JVM 17 experiences a slow heap memory leak (`OutOfMemoryError`) after several days. The application dynamically loads plugins using custom ClassLoaders and caches metadata using a static `WeakHashMap`:

java
public class MetadataRegistry {
    private static final Map<Class<?>, PluginMetadata> metadataCache = new WeakHashMap<>();

    public static void register(Class<?> pluginClass) {
        PluginMetadata metadata = new PluginMetadata(pluginClass);
        metadataCache.put(pluginClass, metadata);
    }
}

public class PluginMetadata {
    private final Class<?> targetClass;
    public PluginMetadata(Class<?> targetClass) {
        this.targetClass = targetClass;
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a Spring `@Transactional` service processes batch uploads. The service loads transient JPA entities, adds them to a custom `HashSet`, persists them, and then tries to check if specific entities exist in the set before executing post-processing. Mysteriously, `HashSet.contains(entity)` returns `false` even though the entity was clearly added to the set earlier.

java
@Entity
public class Account {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String accountNumber;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (!(o instanceof Account)) return false;
        Account account = (Account) o;
        return Objects.equals(id, account.id);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(id);
    }
}
